Answer.Q2_Alternate_Comment: kudoz83 commented on Jan 15Questions/Statements about the proposed functionality - apologies in advance if i'm completely off the mark here:    in OAuth against OpenId Connect, web clients would use an implicit grant type, which does not provide a refresh token. Instead, authorization is re-requested via an iframe using prompt=none and id_token_hint= properties. It would be good if this provided a way to override the re-authorization logic (e.g. don't assume it is via refresh token). I think the idea would be to be able to provide a renewal function, in which we either use http service to perform a refresh via refresh token, or some other logic that is more compliant with the authentication system we're using.    trigger for re-authentication needs to include cases when an authenticated call returns a 401 response, not just when a token is scheduled to expire. If re-authentication fails we need to surface this error to the consumer so they can redirect or something.    AuthHttp needs to handle queuing subsequent requests made through it while awaiting the result of the renewal function. The idea is that renewal should be an atomic operation.
Answer.Q3_Dis_Solution_Comment: It would be good to queue up requests (less important if there is any preemptive refresh mechanism) but that could be handled if needed within the refresh method which is returning an observable. It just needs to keep track if it already has any in-flight request (probably some rxjs operator can make that easy as well as things like retries).
Answer.Q4_Dis_Problem_Comment: chenkie commented on Feb 26Thanks again for this @CaptainCodeman :) As mentioned in the issue, this is better suited to a separate module, which I'd love to collaborate on. Closing this in light of that.

I have two quick thoughts, though they don't really need to be added to the design doc.    It's a pity we can't give at least a little information about the memory layout. It would make this a little more complicated, but the ability to preserve contiguity along a given axis would be nice.    At some point we should add hooks that allow dynamically registered types to specify how they are serialized. Answer.P2_Cores: izaid, talumbau, insertinterestingnamehere, mwiebe
Answer.Q1_Support_Comment: @mrocklin the main benefit I see here is that users would get a memory layout back from the serialized data that roughly matches the one they put in. It would make it so that people whose code is designed to work with a given memory layout wouldn't have to restructure their data in memory every time it is deserialized. That's a choice in both the efficiency and in the interface. That said, it's not a huge issue, just something I think would be nice to have. Distinctions like this are more important for our callables than they are for serialization.
Answer.Q2_Alternate_Comment: Reading over this quickly, it looks good. I have two quick thoughts, though they don't really need to be added to the design doc.It's a pity we can't give at least a little information about the memory layout. It would make this a little more complicated, but the ability to preserve contiguity along a given axis would be nice.At some point we should add hooks that allow dynamically registered types to specify how they are serialized. It should be possible to make it so that if a C++ type we're registering provides the right serialization and deserialization interfaces we automatically register it with the needed callables when the new type is added to our registry.$$$$@mwiebe it feels like a start, though it'd be nice to be able to specify which axis is contiguous rather than just requiring that it be the first or the last one. Ideally there would be a way to mark any particular dimension as contiguous rather than making that be enforced by some syntax layered onto what is, conceptually, the item type. That issue definitely shouldn't hold up our developing a serialization interface though.

Answer.Q1_Support_Comment: Thanks for this work! I will give you a feedback tomorrow, I'm busy today.$$$$I really like this feature, even though personally I wouldn't probably use it, I'm thinking this could be something people could be really interested in. As a podmin I would probably want to somehow restrict abuse of this feature, especially if I use an email service which costs money after X amount of emails (like I personally do, Mandrill in this case). Not sure how this could be restricted neatly..Btw, basing a big feature like this on master is risky since they can be very far away, especially the UI side is almost rewritten in develop (styling parts). If you can't base it on develop, prepare for lots of tweaking once the time comes since it must be merged in to develop.Connecting to the federation: Currently, this pull request only considers the local pod. What is the proper way to extend the code to properly talk to the other pods? I suspect, each pod should be responsible for notifying its local users. Then, the notification should be triggered when posts are created from outside. Where is the proper place to do this?You only need to hook into something that processes posts from the outside, the settings themselves don't need to be federated out. But I think better just hijack some part that doesn't care whether the message is from the outside or inside - I guess StatusMessage model might be one logical place.Translation in other languages: Who is responsible to provide i18n for new features? Currently, this pull request provides en, de and de_formal.Only ever include en in the code - the rest are done via WebTranslateIt.Btw, regarding pushing code to pull requests. To stop mail spam due to automated code review comments to project admins, please try to remember to run pronto locally as in our wiki, and before pushing fix any obvious issues so there is less email spam, thanks!
Answer.Q2_Alternate_Comment: Also, I've adopted the new boostrap-4 css classes.I think we're still on bootstrap3?Does it do any harm if I've included the de translation already? I.e. do I have to remove these translations from the pull request?Yes you should remove any non-en translations, sorry. Once the feature lands, you will be able to do them at WebTranslate.I've thought about that. But wouldn't I expect email delivery being triggered by something like a countroller?If there is email delivery from within the model layer, how would one prevent the system from sending emails when doing maintinance from a rake task or the rails console?TBH, I'm not sure where the notifications/emails are triggered. But unlikely from a controller, since you must consider most of the posts on a pod come from the outside, not via the web UI.But, now that you mention notifications (I think you did), it makes sense to do this in a way that it is not tied to sending emails, but tie it to notifications instead. So then user is able to choose whether to receive emails or not, or just to follow the notifications as regular notifications.For clarification, for example comments trigger notifications to other users, where appropriate. IF the user has the relevant checkbox set in their settings, the notification is delivered also by email. I think doing it the same way would reuse the most code and architecture design - also it would be clearer for the users. What do you think?

Answer.Q1_Support_Comment: Looks good to me. If there are no further comments, I will merge this in a day.
Answer.Q3_Dis_Solution_Comment: IMO, the functionality must be part of the platform (core) and not part of operators library (malhar). It applies to various types of operators like JDBC, S3, HDFS. It should be possible to have any operator configured for synchronous and asynchronious processing.$$$$If every time new functionality is introduced, a completely new operator is also introduced, we will end up with dozens of operators that expose related functionality. Such approach complicates life for an application developer as it becomes confusing which operator out of those dozens to use or extend. IMO, there should be an attempt to reuse and extend existing functionality first and only in case there are technical reasons not to do so, a brand new operator should be introduced.The value of such abstract operator is limited as it does not allow to reuse existing wide range of input and output connectors and functional operators and requires reimplementation of every connector if async processing is necessary (please correct me if I am wrong).For every tuple it processes it creates at minimum 2 additional objects not counting input and output tuples. For high throughput operators, this will lead to extensive GC.While Apex was designed to adjust to the input rate and either propagate back pressure or elastically scale if configured, AbstractAsyncProcessor is configured with the fixed number of threads and if those threads are not capable of keeping up with the input rate, the queue of tuples to process will grow indefinitely, leading to out of memory errors and huge checkpoint snapshots with no way to recover out of this condition.
Answer.Q4_Dis_Problem_Comment: What is the immediate need for this functionality? Are there other malhar operators that depend on the AbstractAsyncProcessor?Why is it necessary to introduce the new operator instead of extending the existing one that provides related functionality?Checkpointing is a joint functionality of the Apex platform and operators. In general, operator should define what state to checkpoint and platform defines how checkpoints are saved and restored.

Answer.Q2_Alternate_Comment: This is going to be confusing, since the JS SDK is one level deeper than the other SDKs:JS ParseObjectJS ObjectState == Android/iOS/.NET ParseObjectJS UniqueInstanceState/SingleInstanceState == Android/iOS/.NET ParseObject.StateDoes ParseReact publicize ObjectState directly? If not, it'd be great if we can rename things to make it less confusing moving between codebases.$$$$So, we could probably abstract everything away and make this a controller, but one of the core reasons that ObjectStore exists, and why single-instance mode is addressable by a className + ID mapping, is to eventually publicize APIs that provide functional access over Parse Objects (a la Parse+React) without requiring any new code.It's still possible to eventually publicize APIs that provide functional access over ParseObjects (a.k.a publicize our current ObjectState) while still abstracting the State store. IMO, it's even more powerful if we abstract it as controller (and the API will allow people to build localStorage based State store! #randomidea #dontmindthis).I agree with passing _getStateIdentifier.

Answer.Q2_Alternate_Comment: Ok, that's better, but I fear it doesn't suffice. We need to gracefully handle runtime errors in setting the ambient capabilities from exec_child() as well. So when a unit contains AmbientCapabilities=, we must detect whether the kernel actually supports that feature. If it does, any error reported from capability_ambient_set_apply() must lead to a hard error. If the kernel does not support this feature, we should not even try to set the ambient caps but simply print a warning and carry on. The logic to detect kernel support should not be called from exec_child() though, but be cached in the manager somehow.Care to take another look? Sorry for not bringing this up earlier!$$$$Just to mention this: in the code base we frequently use 1ULL where we better should have used UINT64_C(1), since we weren't aware of that macro back then. For new code we should really use it though, when we really want to express that something is supposed to be a UINT64 constant.

If you want more you have to add the serializer plugin. That's because not every one need this support and do serializing even if not required would be an useless overhead. That's how and why zend-cache is designed. So if the underlying adapter doesn't support all requirements from psr-6 this wrapper need to implement it on top.

Or is this just for my benefit when checking on your code?Apart from that:I think your improvement is good. But I have a question about the code that was there before...Why would an URL have 4 components (meaning three . in the host)?Also, you might want to create the TLD array somewhere else, so it isn't created each time this method is called. I don't think it will matter much because the method isn't called THAT often, but imho it would be better anyway$$$ HenningJ commented on Apr 20, 2011Don't get me wrong, I do like comments. :-)But I think they should be more about why something is done, not about how something is done. Because I can read the how in the code myself. Unless (of course) it's a really complicated how.So, a comment like// If there's a .if ([stringValue rangeOfString:@"."] .location != NSNotFound) {imho only clutters the code with useless lines. Instead it should be something like// a mail address or url have to contain at least one ., so if it exists, do some more checking on thatThe same goes for// If the string is prefixed with / or ~ it's a file pathif ([stringValue hasPrefix:@"/"] || [stringValue hasPrefix:@"~"]) {I can see its checking for the / and ~ prefixes, so all I need is that this means its a file path.But maybe that's just me.Also, remove the NSLogs :-)$$$
